{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85f87592-8c5e-4885-af23-c73e6ededee0","content":"Use conditional compilation or the `OnPlatform` pattern in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Each platform-specific class lives under `Platforms/<OS>/` and implements `INotificationService`.\n- The `#if` directives ensure only the relevant implementation is compiled per target, so no missing-type errors occur at runtime.\n- An alternative is `DeviceInfo.Platform` with runtime checks, but preprocessor directives are preferred here because platform implementations often reference platform-specific APIs that won't compile cross-platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1a90e39f-ce81-449c-9c9f-0b87bcafb2ff","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection setup for platform-specific services. This is a general knowledge question about MAUI's `MauiProgram.cs` pattern — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"9BD2:11AB75:62441B0:6D80CDA:69EC1053"},"id":"7dddcdf3-99de-4928-89af-92974672e5ab","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:52:43.868Z","parentId":"d2d476d3-83b6-4334-8808-1432fa9e7478"}
